## Canonical State

- `PROJECT_STATE.json`: stage and milestone state. Non-Grill transitions may
  auto-proceed only inside the active Grill Automation Policy and with Gate
  ledger evidence; explicit user confirmation is required for Grill
  exit/delegation, approval-recording tools, actions outside policy, and
  irreversible external submit.
- `iteration_log.json`: experiment history and best iteration. `$iterate` owns writes here.
- `project_map.json`: stable implementation map for core code and configs.
- `docs/context/*.md`: dynamic-context-v2 canonical contracts, facts,
  evidence, protocol, experiments, and memory docs.
- `docs/20_facts/Codebase_Map.md`: legacy/operator-facing stable codebase map when present.
- `docs/_views/` and `docs/_site/`: generated evidence-preview data and
  human-readable HTML views; Markdown remains the source of truth.
- `MEMORY.md`: optional human-readable accepted lessons bank. `iteration_log.json` remains the machine source of truth.
- `OPERATOR_CONTEXT.md`: optional operator preferences. It may guide defaults, but it is not evidence for project facts. Write it only from explicit operator input; later stages read it without inferring new preferences.
- `.evidence/`: evidence-chain artifacts for compiled current docs when the dynamic context layout is enabled.
- `.auto_iterate/`: controller-owned runtime state (if auto-iterate is enabled; do not edit manually).
- `.workflow_supervisor/`: workflow-supervisor-owned runtime state; inspect via
  `tooling/workflow_supervisor/scripts/workflow_ctl.sh`, do not edit manually.
- These canonical state files must stay at the repository root, not under `.agents/`.

## Context Layers

- Read `.agents/references/context-layering-policy.md` and `.agents/references/research-invariants.md` before research planning, documentation, iteration, auto-iteration, or release work.
- Dynamic-context-v2 canonical docs belong in `docs/context/`.
- Current fact-layer summaries belong in `docs/context/facts.md`; they must come from project artifacts or evidence chains.
- Research Conclusion Evidence inputs belong in `docs/context/evidence.md`; they record sources and candidate norms, not permanent rules.
- `.evidence/**` is tool-owned audit state for Evidence Chains, protocol builds, and review packets; do not hand-edit it.
- Dynamic protocol drafts belong in `docs/context/protocol.md`; they are project-local and evidence-derived.
- Human-approved contracts belong in `docs/context/contracts.md`; they override protocol drafts and operator preferences.
- `docs/context/experiments.md` stores the Experiment Queue, mutable
  discoveries, Research Wiki notes, falsifiers, controls, assurance gaps,
  paper-driven run requests, findings, and open questions.
- `docs/context/memory.md` stores candidate and accepted lessons before any
  optional promotion to root `MEMORY.md`.
- Current project facts must come from current repo artifacts, logs, configs, metrics, or evidence chains, not from memory alone.

## Language Policy

- Match the language of the latest substantive user input unless the user explicitly requests another language.
- Use the same language for natural-language artifacts, reports, and summaries unless the user asks for a different output language.
- Keep file names, paths, commands, code identifiers, JSON/YAML keys, schema fields, workflow IDs, metric keys, and placeholder tokens in English.
- Treat English wording in templates and examples under `.agents/` as structural guidance only, not as a requirement that the final output be in English.

## Skills

- Prefer visible aliases first: `$grill`, `$prepare`, `$build`, `$run`,
  `$analyze`, `$write`, and `$change`. Internal skills remain readable route
  targets, not the first operator surface.
- Use `$orchestrator` for stage status, gating, rollback, and project-level decisions.
- Use `$init-project` for WF0 compact guidance setup, staged guidance refresh, and explicit operator-context updates.
- Use `$init-project update-from-grill` immediately after an accepted Grill
  draft to initialize or refresh `CLAUDE.md`, `AGENTS.md`, and `README.md`
  from candidate Grill context without marking WF1-WF3 complete.
- Use `$grill` for draft-only early research intent clarification. After the
  operator confirms `grill_draft_ready`, route directly to
  `$init-project update-from-grill` unless guidance initialization is skipped.
- Use `$prepare` / `$build` through workflow-supervisor for
  `harness prepare/build` runtime status, typed pending requests, and
  worker-result validation.
- Use `$doc-compiler` for contract, fact, protocol, or release docs that need evidence-chain JSON.
- Use `$docs-site` after durable Markdown docs are finalized when
  `docs/_site/**` human-readable HTML should be refreshed; do not use it for
  temporary Markdown drafts.
- Use `$protocol-compiler` to compile `docs/context/evidence.md` into reviewable `docs/context/protocol.md` drafts without field profiles.
- Use `$protocol-drift-check` before turning protocol drafts into contracts or before WF5/WF10/WF11/WF12 gates in dynamic-context projects.
- Use `$review-packet` when the operator needs a short approval/revision/rejection packet for a dynamic-context gate.
- After explicit human approval for a contract, use `tooling/evidence/approve_contract.py` and then re-run the dynamic-context gate.
- Use `$run` for WF10 iteration. The internal `$iterate` source owns
  `iteration_log.json` and follows `action_state.next_action` across `plan`,
  `code`, `run_screening`, `run_full`, `eval`, `debug`, `compare`, `ablate`,
  `register`, `promote`, `discard`, and `stop`.
- Use `$code-expert` only for first-pass implementation from the roadmap and project map.
- Use `$code-debug` for post-WF8 implementation code changes, bug fixes, or iteration-driven edits under `src/`, `scripts/`, `configs/`, or `project_map.json`.
- Use `$harness-maintenance` for Codex hooks, skill contracts, skill routing/triggers, permission policy, `.agents/.claude` skill alignment, and Harness guardrail tests or docs.
- Use `$code-review` for review-only checks of code, diffs, and code-backed docs:
  light during codebase understanding, medium after code changes, heavy when
  docs, evidence chains, release claims, or gate packets depend on the code.
- Use `$evaluate` for experiment analysis and per-iteration reports.
- Use `$idea-debate` as WF2 after WF1 to skeptically compare directions before refinement.
- Use `$refine-idea` as WF3 to turn survey and debate into a feasible, testable idea without architecture design.
- Use `$refine-arch` as WF6 after WF4/WF5 evidence to design the MVP architecture.
- Use `$build-plan` as WF7 to translate architecture into files, tests,
  `project_map.json`, and the operator-facing codebase map doc when present.
- Use the stage-specific skills only for their intended outputs.

## Entry Scripts

- Refer to `CLAUDE.md` for the locked core entry scripts.
